Date: 2026-02-07
Issue: Korean (Hangul) characters not rendering in Zen browser (Flatpak)
Symptom: Korean text displayed as boxes with hex codes (e.g., [68] [C5] [54])

========== ROOT CAUSE ==========

Zen browser is installed via Flatpak, which sandboxes the app.
CJK fonts are installed at /usr/share/fonts/, but Flatpak blocks access to /usr paths.

========== TRIALS ==========

1. Symlink system fonts to user directory → FAILED

   What:
     $ ln -sf /usr/share/fonts/google-noto-sans-cjk-vf-fonts ~/.local/share/fonts/

   Why failed:
     Flatpak sandbox cannot follow symlinks pointing outside the sandbox.
     The symlink target (/usr/share/fonts/...) is inaccessible, so the symlink
     resolves to nothing from Flatpak's perspective.

2. Flatpak filesystem override → FAILED

   What:
     $ flatpak override --user --filesystem=/usr/share/fonts:ro app.zen_browser.zen

   Why failed:
     /usr is a reserved path that Flatpak protects regardless of user overrides.
     The override was accepted but had no effect - Flatpak still refused to
     expose /usr/share/fonts to the sandbox.

3. Copy font files to user directory → SUCCESS

   What:
     $ cp -r /usr/share/fonts/google-noto-sans-cjk-vf-fonts ~/.local/share/fonts/
     $ cp -r /usr/share/fonts/google-noto-serif-cjk-vf-fonts ~/.local/share/fonts/
     $ cp -r /usr/share/fonts/google-noto-sans-mono-cjk-vf-fonts ~/.local/share/fonts/
     $ fc-cache -fv ~/.local/share/fonts

   Why worked:
     ~/.local/share/fonts/ is in the user's home directory, which Flatpak
     exposes to sandboxed apps by default. Physical copies avoid all symlink
     and /usr path restrictions.

========== TAKEAWAY ==========

When Flatpak apps can't access system fonts:
- Symlinks don't work (sandbox can't follow them outside)
- Filesystem overrides to /usr don't work (reserved path)
- Copying fonts to ~/.local/share/fonts/ works (always accessible)

Actual fix: ./2026-02-10-flatpak-fontconfig-fix.log
